===============================================================================
SIMPLE WEB STACK - EXPLANATION
===============================================================================

What happens when you type "www.foobar.com" in a browser?

## STEP 1: REQUEST

The user types "www.foobar.com" in the browser (the application used to visit
websites). The browser needs to find the server's IP address to communicate
with it.

## STEP 2: DNS RESOLUTION

The browser queries the DNS (Domain Name System). It acts as the phonebook
of the Internet, translating human-readable domain names into machine-readable
IP addresses (8.8.8.8).

- "www" is a subdomain configured via an A RECORD that points directly to
  the server's IP address (8.8.8.8).

## STEP 3: CONNECTION TO THE SERVER (THE PROTOCOL)

Now that the browser has retrieved the IP address 8.8.8.8 thanks to the DNS,
it sends an HTTP request. The server uses the TCP/IP PROTOCOL SUITE (via
PORT 80 for HTTP) to establish a reliable connection with the user's computer.

## STEP 4: INSIDE THE SERVER

A SERVER is a physical machine (a powerful computer) or a Virtual Machine
(VM / Container) in the Cloud designed to provide information or services
to other computers. Inside this server, the request goes through the stack:

- WEB SERVER (Nginx): It is the first component to receive the request on
  port 80. If it is a static page, it sends it back. If it is dynamic content,
  it forwards the request.
- APPLICATION SERVER: It receives the request from Nginx, executes the code
  (the Application files / codebase) to generate the page dynamically.
- DATABASE (MySQL): To build the page (for example, retrieving user profile
  information), the application server queries the MySQL database.

## STEP 5: THE RESPONSE

The database replies to the app server -> the app server replies to Nginx ->
Nginx sends the final HTML/CSS page back via the TCP/IP connection.
The browser displays the website.

===============================================================================
ISSUES WITH THIS INFRASTRUCTURE
===============================================================================

- SPOF (Single Point of Failure):
  There is only ONE server. If it catches fire, powers off, or crashes, the
  entire website goes offline instantly.

- DOWNTIME:
  If I want to update my code (deployment), I often have to restart or manipulate
  the services, which cuts off access to other users during that time.

- SCALABILITY:
  If 10,000 users arrive at the same time, the CPU, RAM, or MySQL will overload
  (too many QPS - Queries Per Second), and the server will crash.
